task.summary: Default task
Updated to new IDE.
Gutted. Nearly a full recode started.

Reworking the processing. Decided to store sentences in a list of Sentence objects as per new directives from Avery Baggett to process sentences this way. Also makes more sense. Split the XML parser into two subroutines as the old code was difficult to understand and there are two distinct versions.
Finished initial draft of Lyon processor.
Second processor subroutine added, should be able to get a list of sentence objects now.
First phase of processor testing, seems to work. Cannot generate CSV file as template from Avery Baggett is blank.
Added the NLTK POS Tagger -- works beautifully. Also added a guide to the tag meanings. Now each sentence is tagged as it is read into the object.
Corrections to the list of POS tags. Had some remnants of being copied from HTML.
Fixed some bugs, implemented spacy's French language POS tagged. Corrected for punctuation marks within the corpus data (maybe).
Output to a JSON file for later processing. Also added code to get adjective/noun groupings.
Started work on a JSON processor for manual editing of data. Data set requires human intervention to ensure adjectives are correctly tagged.

Added JSON files to work with and got the load, save, and merge JSON functions written. Believe I've done the blacklist and whitelist building correctly now and should merge the data nicely once verified.
Updated JSON files with latest reviewed versions.
Added counters and updated the blacklist and whitelist.
Latest batch of processed data.
Updated for latest data review.
Updated for latest data review.
Updated for latest data review.
Updated for latest data review.
Updated for latest data review.
Final batch of verified data.
Removed some outdated files, changed naming convention to make it easier for Avery's screen reader to look at the code, began work on lemmatizing the data.
Still changing the names of some functions and variables for the screen reader. Added ability to save lemma data (root forms) to the JSON file.
Added a backup of the verified data, compressed. This will prevent any changes to the canonical data which took so long to go through.
Added a bit to save the lemma data to a new file, have not actually created the file yet. Emailed Avery to find out what data she wants exactly so I can code it.
Spoke with Avery, save all data with lemmatized words and generated CSV files to make an excel spreadsheet with for easy reading.
Generated a numbers sheet with actual counts of each adjective.
Making adjustments to the blacklist to remove the last of the bad data and make some other corrections.
This should be the final edits for the last of the special cases.
More processing, split by age after texting with Avery about what she needed next.
Update from Avery, up to age 8 is the cut off, not up to and including age 8.

Finally got rid of the last of the bad / weird data. I'm sure there is some code that needs to be deleted now too as it's outdated. Still need to write the code to laod the lemmatized data from the adjusted JSON.
Breakdown by adjective position and age.
Working on the latest numbers, counting colors and their positions as well as generating a heat-map style grid of adjective/noun pairs and positions.
Output for colors should work now, still have to test it.
Still working on the noun/adjective counts.
Still working on the noun/adjective counts.
First prototype code for generating noun/adjective matrix of counts.
Still working out the kinks of the matrix code. Needing to reduce the noun set as well since otherwise it overloads numbers with too many columns.
Working so far, nouns require validation.
New kinds of validation all over the place. Redid the repair function.
Added data to calculate adjective/noun norms.
Refactoring to structure most of the functions into a package to more easily split the script into individual scripts rather than one massive script.
Basic XML parser for speaker data, though we don't care about the speakers for the CEFC data.
Began work on reading the actual sentence data.
Should be pulling the sentences into the proper data structure so it can be examined.
